        i: { speak: "Does the weather where you live affect your mood? Describe how you feel in different seasons and what you do about it.", tip: "Think about light, temperature, rain — and be honest about seasonal affect. Use 'tends to', 'makes me feel', 'I find that...'", microLabel: "Vocab micro-task", microTitle: "Untranslatable weather words", microInstruction: "Petrichor (the smell of rain on earth), the German 'Schnapsidee' (an idea that only sounds good when drunk in bad weather), the Welsh 'hiraeth' (melancholy longing often tied to grey weather). Find one weather-related word from any language that you love.", microExample: "<strong>Example:</strong> Scottish Gaelic has 'smirr' for very fine drizzle. Can you find something similar in your target language?" },
        a: { speak: "Writers have always used weather to mirror inner states — pathetic fallacy. Choose a piece of writing, film, or your own experience where weather carried emotional meaning. Analyse it.", tip: "Go beyond the obvious — stormy weather for sadness. Find something more nuanced: fog for uncertainty, bright cold for loneliness, thick heat for desire.", microLabel: "Vocab micro-task", microTitle: "Meteorological metaphors", microInstruction: "List five metaphors in your target language that use weather to describe human states or situations. Are these the same in other languages you know?", microExample: "<strong>Example:</strong> 'The calm before the storm', 'every cloud has a silver lining', 'she's under the weather'. Now find equivalents — or contrasts — in your target language." },
