        i: { speak: "What number defines your life right now — your age, years in a place, hours of sleep, days until something? Talk about the numbers that are on your mind.", tip: "Use ordinals (first, second), fractions (half, a third), approximations (about, roughly, nearly). Push your number vocabulary beyond basic counting.", microLabel: "Vocab micro-task", microTitle: "Number idioms", microInstruction: "How many number idioms can you recall in your target language? Think about: 'a hundred percent', 'at the eleventh hour', 'in seventh heaven', 'back to square one'.", microExample: "<strong>Example:</strong> 'At the eleventh hour' means at the last possible moment. Does your target language have an equivalent — or a completely different idiom for the same idea?" },
        a: { speak: "The mathematician Leopold Kronecker said 'God made the integers, all else is the work of man.' What does the human obsession with measuring and quantifying everything — happiness, productivity, beauty — say about us?", tip: "Think about ratings, metrics, scores, targets. Is quantification making us better thinkers or reducing complex things to empty numbers?", microLabel: "Vocab micro-task", microTitle: "Numerically loaded vocabulary", microInstruction: "Some numbers carry cultural or historical weight beyond their mathematical meaning — 7, 13, 40, 666, 42. Choose three numbers that carry special meaning in your culture or target language's culture and explain why.", microExample: "<strong>Example:</strong> In China, 8 is lucky (sounds like 'prosperity'). In Italy, 17 is unlucky (in Roman numerals XVII is an anagram of VIXI, 'I have lived', i.e. I am dead)." },
